"&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWritten evidence submitted by Global Partners Governance&#xa0;\nAbout the authorGreg Power has been involved in political and parliamentary reform for around 20 years. He co-founded Global Partners in 2005 to deliver projects to strengthen representative politics\n, since working in countries in the Middle East, sub-Saharan Africa and Latin America\n.\n \n \nHe \nprovides direct support to politicians and ministers, developing strategies and helping to manage the process of political \nand parliamentary reform\n.\n \n \n&#xa0;\nHe has also provided advice to a variety of international organisations and donor agencies helping, amongst others, the Danish foreign ministry to establish their multi-party institute, and International IDEA to evaluate their work on political parties.\n \n He writes widely on issues such as the application of political economy analysis, donor approaches to governance assistance, and parliamentary transparency. \n \nHe is the author of the first \nGlobal Parliamentary Report\n, published by the UNDP and IPU in 2012.\n&#xa0;\nSummary&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe role of the Burmese parliament in the process of transition.&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nInternational assistance to strengthen parliaments&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe politics of parliamentary strengthening&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\ni\n. \n              \nCommittees as models of good practice.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nii.\n              \nBuilding i\nnstitutional memory\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\niii.\n              \nThe importance of staff and internal structures\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nConclusion: Parliament and political transition&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nNovember \n2013\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \n Power, G. (2011), \nThe Politics of Parliamentary Strengthening\n - \nwww.gpgovernance.net/publication/the-politics-of-parliamentary-strengthening/\n \nSee Power, G. and Shoot, R. (\neds\n), (2012), \nPolitical Parties in Transition\n, DIPD\n,\n which was launched in Yangon in February this year and is now available in Burmese.\n  \nwww.gpgovernance.net/publication/political-parties-in-democratic-transitions/\n"